        <h3 class={h3}>What Are the First-Year Setup Costs?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Cage, Perches, Vet and Food</h4>
        <p class={p}>The big first-year items are a large, safe <a href="/blog/african-grey-parrot-cage-setup/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228">cage and its perches</a>, a first avian-vet wellness visit, and a few months of good pelleted food and fresh produce. Buy the cage right the first time — a cramped or unsafe one costs more in stress, vet bills and replacement than simply buying well at the start.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>A realistic first-year budget</h5>
        <p class={p}>Add it up and a sensible first year beyond the bird runs about $1,100 on the lean end to $2,400 if you go premium on the cage and setup. Shipping belongs in that first-year figure too: our Greys travel on <a href="https://www.iata.org/en/programs/cargo/live-animals/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IATA Live Animals Regulations-compliant ↗</a> flights — $185 to your nearest airport, $350 home. That's the honest number competitors' "just the price" headlines leave out — and knowing it up front is exactly what separates a happy owner from an overwhelmed one.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>What Does It Cost Every Year After That?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Food, Vet and Toy Replacement</h4>
        <p class={p}>Once you're set up, the running costs settle down: pelleted food and fresh produce ($200–$400), an annual avian-vet wellness check ($75–$200), and a steady replacement of toys a Grey will happily shred ($100–$250). Call it $400–$1,100 a year for a healthy bird in a normal year.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Budgeting for the unexpected vet bill</h5>
        <p class={p}>The line everyone forgets is the one that bites: the unexpected vet bill. African Greys hide illness, and an emergency avian visit can run into the hundreds fast. Keep a small buffer ($0–$500 a year, realistically) so a sick bird is a phone call, not a financial crisis — it's the kindest insurance you can give a 40–60 year companion.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: the 40–60 year commitment</h6>
        <p class={p}>We say it to every buyer: an African Grey can outlive the decade you're planning around — they live 40 to 60 years. The purchase price is a rounding error against a lifetime of food, vet care and time. Buy the bird because you want the relationship for the long haul, not because the number on day one felt affordable.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 10. H2-5 Worth it -->
        <h2 id="worth" class={h2}>Is an African Grey Worth the Price?</h2>
        <p class={p}>Honestly? For the right home, an African Grey is worth every dollar — and for the wrong one, no price is low enough. Worth isn't really about the figure; it's about whether you want a brilliant, demanding, decades-long companion that talks back. If you do, the question stops being "is it expensive?" and becomes "which Grey, and what should I budget?"</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Congo vs Timneh — Which Is the Better Value?</h3>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-5 my-6">
          <figure class="m-0">
            <img src="/congo-african-grey-variant.webp" width="640" height="480" alt="A Congo African Grey with its classic red tail — the larger subspecies at $1,700–$2,500" title="Congo African Grey value | C.A.Gs" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
            <span class={figc}>Congo — larger, red tail, $1,700–$2,500, classically clear talker.</span>
          </figure>
          <figure class="m-0">
            <img src="/baby-timneh-african-grey-evie-training-plan.webp" width="600" height="509" alt="A baby Timneh African Grey — the smaller, value subspecies at $1,500–$1,600" title="Timneh African Grey value | C.A.Gs" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
            <span class={figc}>Timneh — smaller, maroon tail, $1,500–$1,600, often an earlier talker.</span>
          </figure>
        </div>
        <p class={p}>On pure value the Timneh wins on price and tends to settle and start talking a little sooner; the Congo costs a touch more for its size and famously clear speech. But the gap is modest and the documentation is identical, so the better value is simply the bird whose temperament fits your home — not the cheaper line on a spec sheet.</p>

